	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />An emulator of a patent-expired console doesn't infringe.
<br />
<br />Which narrows the question: If the NES patent <em>hadn't</em> expired, such as in the case of a <a href="http://www.kuro5hin.org/story/2003/1/22/141540/716" class="postlink">Cher Patent Act</a>, would an emulator infringe? Does a PlayStation emulator infringe? My guess is no because <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sony_Computer_Entertainment,_Inc._v._Connectix_Corporation" class="postlink">Sony lost to Connectix</a> and Bleem in court, despite winning the war by bankrupting both companies with attorney's fees, forcing Bleem to close and Connectix to sell its assets to Microsoft and Sony.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


